    \section{Markov Transition Matrix between Delinquency
Statuses}\label{markov-transition-matrix-between-delinquency-statuses}

This technical report is oriented to calculate the probability matrix in
the "actual" dataset to see the next month distribution. The following
transition matrix were taken in account: Transition Matrix for all loans
in a single markov chain in the full dataset, Transition Matrix for a
markov chain per loan in the full dataset, Transition Matrix per Loan
without consecutive Paid-Off status' in the full dataset, Transition
Matrix per Loan without invalid transitions and consecutive Paid-Off
status for Subprime, Prime and full dataset and Transition Matrix for
unknown type of loans. There are some open questions for further
discussions.

    \subsection{Transitions between
statuses}\label{transitions-between-statuses}

From Paper (Sirignano et. al, 2017):

"A mortgage is determined to be 1 month delinquent if no payment has
been made by the last day of the month and the payment was due on the
ﬁrst day of the month."

"The transition matrices highlight that mortgages frequently transition
back and forth between current and various delinquency states.
Disruptions in cashﬂow to the lender or servicer are common due to the
mortgage being behind payment. Similarly, even loans that are extremely
delinquent may return to current; the transition from foreclosed back to
current is actually a relatively frequent occurrence. A foreclosure
could get cured via paying the outstanding balance, there could be a
pre-auction sale that covers all or some of the amount outstanding, or
there could be a sale at the foreclosure auction that covers all or some
of the amount outstanding. Any of these will register as a foreclosure
to paid oﬀ transition. Mortgages can also transition directly from
current, 30 days delinquent, 60 days delinquent, or 90+ days delinquent
to REO via a 'deed in lieu of foreclosure' ".

    \begin{Verbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
{\color{incolor}In [{\color{incolor}11}]:} \PY{k}{def} \PY{n+nf}{transition\PYZus{}matrix}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{,} \PY{n}{transitions}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}
             \PY{n}{transition\PYZus{}chain} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n+nb}{zip}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{transitions}\PY{p}{,}\PY{n}{transitions}\PY{p}{[}\PY{l+m+mi}{1}\PY{p}{:}\PY{p}{]}\PY{p}{)}
             \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{} print(\PYZsq{}size: \PYZsq{}, len(list(transition\PYZus{}chain)))}
             \PY{k}{for} \PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{i}\PY{p}{,}\PY{n}{j}\PY{p}{)} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n+nb}{zip}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{transitions}\PY{p}{,}\PY{n}{transitions}\PY{p}{[}\PY{l+m+mi}{1}\PY{p}{:}\PY{p}{]}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}
                 \PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{[}\PY{n}{i}\PY{p}{]}\PY{p}{[}\PY{n}{j}\PY{p}{]} \PY{o}{+}\PY{o}{=} \PY{l+m+mi}{1}      
         
         \PY{k}{def} \PY{n+nf}{probabilities\PYZus{}matrix}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}    
             \PY{k}{for} \PY{n}{row} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{:}
                 \PY{n}{s} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n+nb}{sum}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{row}\PY{p}{)}
                 \PY{k}{if} \PY{n}{s} \PY{o}{\PYZgt{}} \PY{l+m+mi}{0}\PY{p}{:}
                     \PY{n}{row}\PY{p}{[}\PY{p}{:}\PY{p}{]} \PY{o}{=} \PY{p}{[}\PY{n}{f}\PY{o}{/}\PY{n}{s} \PY{k}{for} \PY{n}{f} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n}{row}\PY{p}{]}    
\end{Verbatim}


    \subsection{Transition Matrix for all loans in a single markov
chain}\label{transition-matrix-for-all-loans-in-a-single-markov-chain}

This function considers all original labels in a single markov chain and
then calculates the transitions between statuses.

    \begin{Verbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
{\color{incolor}In [{\color{incolor}12}]:} \PY{k}{def} \PY{n+nf}{markov\PYZus{}tmatrix\PYZus{}all\PYZus{}loans}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}
             \PY{n}{n} \PY{o}{=} \PY{l+m+mi}{1}\PY{o}{+} \PY{n+nb}{max}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{)} \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{}number of statuses}
             \PY{n}{M} \PY{o}{=} \PY{p}{[}\PY{p}{[}\PY{l+m+mi}{0}\PY{p}{]}\PY{o}{*}\PY{n}{n} \PY{k}{for} \PY{n}{\PYZus{}} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n+nb}{range}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{n}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{]}
             \PY{n}{transition\PYZus{}matrix}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{,} \PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{)}
             \PY{k}{return} \PY{n}{M}
\end{Verbatim}

    \subsection{Transition Matrix for a markov chain per
loan}\label{transition-matrix-for-a-markov-chain-per-loan}

Taking in account the loans by separate, it is not considered spurious
states: false states between loans and loans with a single record.

    \begin{Verbatim}[commandchars=\\\{\}]
{\color{incolor}In [{\color{incolor}13}]:} \PY{k}{def} \PY{n+nf}{markov\PYZus{}tmatrix\PYZus{}per\PYZus{}loan}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{data}\PY{p}{,} \PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}
             \PY{n}{n} \PY{o}{=} \PY{l+m+mi}{1}\PY{o}{+} \PY{n+nb}{max}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{)} \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{}number of states}
             \PY{n}{M} \PY{o}{=} \PY{p}{[}\PY{p}{[}\PY{l+m+mi}{0}\PY{p}{]}\PY{o}{*}\PY{n}{n} \PY{k}{for} \PY{n}{\PYZus{}} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n+nb}{range}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{n}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{]}
             
             \PY{n}{loan\PYZus{}id} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n}{data}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{groupby}\PY{p}{(}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{l+s+s1}{LOAN\PYZus{}ID}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{[}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{l+s+s1}{LOAN\PYZus{}ID}\PY{l+s+s1}{\PYZsq{}}\PY{p}{]}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{count}\PY{p}{(}\PY{p}{)}    
             \PY{n}{i} \PY{o}{=}\PY{l+m+mi}{0}
             \PY{k}{for} \PY{n}{lid}\PY{p}{,} \PY{n}{count} \PY{o+ow}{in} \PY{n}{loan\PYZus{}id}\PY{o}{.}\PY{n}{items}\PY{p}{(}\PY{p}{)}\PY{p}{:}        
                 \PY{n}{labels\PYZus{}id} \PY{o}{=} \PY{n}{labels}\PY{p}{[}\PY{n}{i}\PY{p}{:}\PY{n}{i}\PY{o}{+}\PY{n}{count}\PY{p}{]} \PY{c+c1}{\PYZsh{} to separate by rows belonging to the same loan.                }
                 \PY{n}{transition\PYZus{}matrix}\PY{p}{(}\PY{n}{M}\PY{p}{,} \PY{n}{labels\PYZus{}id}\PY{p}{)}
                 \PY{n}{i} \PY{o}{+}\PY{o}{=} \PY{n}{count}    
             \PY{k}{return} \PY{n}{M}
\end{Verbatim}

    \subsection{Dropping invalid transitions between delinquency
statuses:}\label{dropping-invalid-transitions-between-delinquency-statuses}

Invalid transitions that are present in our current transition matrix:
\{current -\/-\textgreater{} 60, current -\/-\textgreater{}90, 30
-\/-\textgreater{} 90, REO -\/-\textgreater{} any other state (except
itself??), PAID-OFF -\/-\textgreater{} any other state (except
itself??)\}

From Paper (Sirignano et. al, 2017):

"Monthly mortgage transitions from current to 60 days delinquent or from
30 days delinquent to 90+ days delinquent are not possible. Errors of
this type are very infrequent in the dataset and we remove those samples
where such errors occur."

"Certain transitions are not allowed in the dataset (e.g., current to 60
days delinquent). Although such a transition is theoretically allowed in
the formulation (2), the transition probabilities of transitions which
do not occur in the dataset will be driven to zero during training." (by
changing the predicted output in a hard-coded way???)
